Description: CVE-2026-41992 - gzip: don't mishandle .lzh after .Z
 GNU gzip has a global buffer over-read in its LZH decompression logic.
 The `left` and `right` Huffman-tree arrays used by unlzh.c are shared
 with the LZ77/LZW decompression routines and are not reinitialized
 between files processed in the same invocation. An attacker can craft
 an LZW (.Z) file followed by an LZH (.lzh) file processed in a single
 `gzip -d` invocation to poison the shared state; the LZH decoder in
 read_c_len then follows stale values left in the shared array, causing
 reads past the end of the allocated global buffer.
 .
 Fixed upstream by clearing left/right in unlzh.c read_c_len when n == 0.
Origin: upstream, https://cgit.git.savannah.gnu.org/cgit/gzip.git/commit/?id=63dbf6b3b9e6e781df1a6a64e609b10e23969681
Author: Paul Eggert <eggert@cs.ucla.edu>
Last-Update: 2026-07-01

--- a/unlzh.c
+++ b/unlzh.c
@@ -242,6 +242,12 @@
         c = getbits(CBIT);
         for (i = 0; i < NC; i++) c_len[i] = 0;
         for (i = 0; i < 4096; i++) c_table[i] = c;
+
+        /* Needed in case LEFT and RIGHT are reused from a previous
+           LZW decompression.  It may be overkill to clear all of both
+           arrays, but nobody has had time to analyze this carefully.  */
+        memzero(left, (2 * NC - 1) * sizeof *left);
+        memzero(right, (2 * NC - 1) * sizeof *left);
     } else {
         i = 0;
         while (i < n) {
